Comment: Day 2 flash. Spent so much damn time messing up the beta my first time here. Was pretty easy the second time around with the correct method.
More like the sweathouse! This boulder was roasting! Jacob has cousins named Joan, Jean, Jane, and....DAWSON.
Fun fact: my dad LOVES pony rides. I did this because I had no hope of doing the cotton pony dyno move, but it was actually pretty good!
Mackenzie didn't understand why I topped out backwards....UNTIL SHE DID IT TOO. Then we proceeded to get our asses kicked on fricken everything else at this sector.
Scary last move in the Nikes!
SHOW EM UR DICK TEDDY!
Does this count as my first outdoor lead? There were bolts on top!
CHASIN THEM STARS.
Lesson of the day: The raisins are ants, the celery is the log, and the peanut butter is the log filling. Still not sure what the "hidden beta" was.

Third time's the charm. Made the topout real sexy. I finally understand why Teddy didn't top this out...he wouldn't have remembered what to call it on 8a. Kelly's Problem? Nicole's Problem? All girl names are the same.

Boulder Name: Played It Like A Poop Butt
Comment: THIS WAS A V0+, WHAT IS THAT ON THE FONT SCALE?!?!

~10 tries. It was at this point that I realized most of Leavenworth was developed by gigantic lumberjacks, since the dyno was a "hold the swing" crux. Gigantic lumberjacks can jump much further than I can, but I can hold on during a swing easier than they can. It'd be cool to be good at both though.

~10 tries. I did a semi difficult flat wall!! So what that it's a one move wonder, sharp, and not the coolest problem overall, I'm very proud of myself, and that's what's important. I also did a badass lumberjack style log roll (aka standing on a dead piece of wood, having it roll away, and landing on my buttocks. SUPLEX'D).
A very nice looking problem, but doesn't climb quite as nice.
One day I will flash a vertical/slab problem harder than V1.
The last pain free boulder in Leavenworth after hurting my wrist on Pimpsqueak. One day Mackenzie and I will both be healthy at the same time.
Went off-route on the flash attempt. Fun getting to practice my dynos.
My hands numbed out on the flash attempt. High crux kinda freaked me out.
So many sucker holds! Cool boulder
Climbs really well once your fingers get warm enough to feel the holds!

Not the best thing I've ever climbed, but gave me some hope that I might be able to top some things out in Roy. Unfortunately, that wasn't super true. Roy is hard (and kinda scary, and sometimes a little chossy :/). Also I did 4 hand moves on the same 2 holds which was kinda unique.
Best problem I did in Roy. Slowly getting better at flatwall (thanks to Mackenzie).

Boulder Name: Nobody Gets Out of Here Alive
Comment: Bookended the trip with sweet V2s. This was my project....AND I SENT!!
Had to wait until everybody else topped out and I was the only one left in the cold, dark cave.
Probably the hardest flat wall I've ever done. Had to think "Keep Going".http://bit.ly/keep_going_video
"Once again, that is not the lip". Wise words from Conor as I informed him that, "I'm just going to jump" and proceeded to hold onto a nothing hold. Everybody on the ground was stoked on me.

A combo of Castle Rock (yus), and palming a basketball (double yus). Gave myself 20 mins before the sun was gonna destroy the sloper, but only needed 15. Though, in classic fashion, I nearly botched the topout.

I was super confident that the name was referring to clawing at this pinch like a lobster. Then I was told it's because it looks like a gigantic lobster claw. It broke my world into a million tiny pieces. I grabbed a sick non-hold on the flash attempt. Conor and Mackenzie were extremely impressed and kept saying how cool I was.
Not quite as good as Ides, but still pretty good.
Surprised I didn't dab on the rock behind during the lower moves. Climbing with non-numb fingeys is >>>> climbing with numb fingeys.

Brrrr. Kinda scary topout as I was fully numb and didn't know if I was holding onto the hold or not. First day being guided by Kwang. He didn't remember telling me about the pee trail in Squamish back in 2013. Rude.
That weird heel move almost destroyed my hamstring, but I'm a god damn warrior so I just endured the pain. Jk. I bitched about it a lot.
Slippery feet -> blinded by the light over the lip. Apparently that song (Blinded by the Light) was done by Manfred Mann's Earth Band, which is a sweet name.
Went left hand first. For some reason I have really fond memories of this one.
Fuck yes I started slightly lower so I could get that sweet, sweet bonus V-grade. Did this one after putting on a falling clinic (pro tip: go limp) on Choir Boys.
The rock was really cold but this problem warmed my heart. Also, I dabbed on the opening move, but it doesn't matter. Nothing matters.
Probably should have had a plan for what to do past the 3rd move so I wouldn't go full Thrutch King on the easier moves. Whatever, still sick.
Looks pretty dumb, climbs pretty well. Shoutout to my down jacket for providing endless entertainment with its sweet worm arms.
HQ warmup. I like jugs.
All I remember is it being pretty warm and wanting to take a nap in the sun. Also Conor did that sick 4 to the right and it was sick as hell.
I think this one was pretty fun? Don't fully understand why it's so popular though.
Shoutout to Kenneth Brian Edmonds. This one was pretty fun; good job Hueco! Way to set fun problems!
First problem in Hueco! Access is a gift. This place is a gift. Stoney guy is a gift. Oh, Conor had a fucking SIACK pad ascent on this too.

Needed a confidence boost and this definitely delivered. It's about time the homie Tom Moulin put up a softie instead of brutally stiff problems like Ultraviolet. Fun double dyno (one of the few times I've successfully gone all 4 points off).

Really good, and not that scary with 4 pads. I even took a backsplat and was totally fine. The trick to survival is to power your body off when you start falling. The trick to doing the problem is to grab a non-existent sloper.

Hardest fart ascent to date. You know you're having a good time when the number of farts > number of moves. I used perfect beta too. If you want to know exactly how to do this boulder, hmu for good tips (it involves cutting your feet and getting confused).
Incredible problem. Glad I re-climbed it, since my first ascent was fugly as hell. Jolie cruised this on the 2nd session of the day; I think the first time I've seen that work?
Got some SIACK shots of Teddy and Mackenzie on this rig. I may climb like shit, but at least I can take beautiful photographs.
Really fun. It sucks that I'm awful at this style of climbing because it's really fun when I'm able to do stuff.
Not very fun. Not very pretty. On a boulder that gets slammed by people. Why is this one popular?
Someday I'll be able to climb the actual "classic" problems in Bishop instead of going around climbing second-tier problems because they're less crowded

Slightly dabbed on the flash :( Guess I feel okay about it since not dabbing was probably the crux for me. As long as you have a ~68 inch wingspan, this is soft. If not, it probably starts to get waaaay harder.

So nice I climbed it twice. Fell off the awkward-not-hard topout the first time I got through the bottom. Thankfully it's really soft (only one hard move, which may not even be hard if I knew how to do a kneebar?). Still, I almost didn't finish after botching the topout because my crimping abilities had been depleted.
Hopped on this to do the bottom moves to warm up, ended up getting flash pumped and nearly botched the top because I was climbing so sloppily.
Couldn't hold the swing going RH first, but did it first try after deciding to try to go LH like Mackenzie.
Real good compression problem. Super pleasant evening send after driving over from Joe's to avoid the Festival.
Not super secure at the top; a couple of the jugs feel a little sketch.
An annoyingly tricky topout, but this area (The Flu) is really sweet. Huge shoutout to the dudes who developed/recorded/guidebooked/made the trail up to these boulders.
Only one hard move, but a pretty sweet victory dyno/topout.
Way harder than it looks and I almost botched the V3 topout (also Mackenzie went V0-V7 today, which was pretty sweet).
Not a great problem, but reminded me of a great internet picture:http://bit.ly/a_very_big_boy
Total fluke. Pulled on just to remember how to do the come-in move and ended up taking it to the top. Like 6th try this year (after like 600 last time I was here).
A little bit of Castle Rock in Utah!
Spicy up top! Climbs way better than it looks (since it looks a little crumbly)
I DID A FLATWALL! Plus I totally called it, telling Mackenzie, "Watch out! This boy's taking it to the top!"Honestly don't know if I've ever been happier to do a boulder.
Thuggy and powerful on a cool lip feature. The weird RH holds limit it from getting the recommended flag.
Didn't use a heel, cuz fuck heels. Also managed to miss both of the large pads (nearly 40 ft^2!) from about 4 feet off the ground because I rocket off holds occasionally.
I almost threw a "Hard" on this, but I think the first time I tried it I was just pooped since it went 1st go on the 2nd day (and didn't feel super strenuous).
Pretty good, but a little spicy at the top (even without any dynoing).
This problem was not as fun. Pockets don't make for the best warmups.
This problem was legitimately really good. I'm not 100% sure why, but it is (or maybe I was just stoked that day?).
FWIW, this would be one of the best problems at CRSP. \_()_/
Did it from a half move in cuz I'm a gosh danged IDIOT. 100% not worth the hike, but 100% worth the hot stone massage.
Hashtag crushing the hashtag boulders.
World class pad slide under this problem. Maybe one days I'll psych up for the boulder transfer to Wave Catcher.
I topped a boulder and Mackenzie picked up her car; gg weekend #2. Too bad I pulled a full Johnny Hekker on the Buttload of Sausage.
I topped a boulder and Mackenzie bought a car; gg weekend. A CBarth Original and prob a bit better than Girls on Film, since it's a bit more sustained.

Fun roof-jug climbing other than the lone crux move, but if you were tall or had long arms I don't know if this would feel harder than like V6 (maybe the post-crux big move might feel more cramped though?) Had to dyno to the tooth jug cuz I'm not very long, and also didn't want to risk hurting my knee/ankle on that twisty heel hook.

Glad I could slay this nemesis with the help of Teddy's tall(er) man beta. Did the top out so so clean. My feet never cut, I didn't one arm lockoff an intermediate, and I definitely didn't grab any moss or anything. Mackenzie cried again watching me, I guess I'm just that inspirational.
Fun powerful climbing, and a cool mantle move over the lip (did it with a toe under the roof instead of the heel hook method). Wish there were more lines like this.

This is really just training for my future super project Lie Down to Sit Down to Stand Up to Sit Down to Holm Boy. I like this type of sloper traversing, where you say fuck technique and mostly campus the cruxy move.
So hard for me. Had to really mess around with the beta for nearly every move to make it fell doable. Shoutout to my new Quebecois friends on Tim's Sloper Problem during the final session.
Pretty similar to Golden Boy but maybe a touch harder and a touch better?
First outdoor boulder in over 12 months after ankle surgery; maybe I should have picked something smaller? Super good, but a little dirty up top.
(Picking up the superfly rock). Proudest ascent to date. Thanks to Keenan for the support, Mackenzie for the video, and basketballs for being a great training device.
Weird first move and I felt like every topout hold may break. Unfortunately it started raining right after this, but the other problems at Cat Lake look like they could be pretty sick!

Felt like an epic, even though I only pulled on maybe a dozen times. After the start hold broke, people are calling this V10? Still think it's in the V9 range, there's really only one hard move before the mantel, and I didn't think it was that bad. Botched the topout on the 3rd go in classic Connor Reed fashion. Eventually had to use the mantel beta that was told to me instead of the beta that felt comfortable. Only thing that takes away from this problem is the brokeness of the start holds.
Really tough for me. Had to put my big boy pants on and pull 100%. The move after the big move was almost a devastator.

OH FUCK SO SICK. Pretty scary topping out. Can't believe it all came together finally. This problem may only be 20 inches off the ground, but it feels much taller, maybe 22 inches! Shoutout to Mackenzie for the encouragement and beta. Would give it 10 stars if I could.
Shoutout CRSP for prepping me for this. Reminds me of Duct Tape.
"I just fell on a V0-". I think it's sandbagged. Probably closer to V0+
Kinda randomly ended up here looking for something at the end of the day. This problem was actually pretty fun despite being 5 feet tall.
Maybe should have flashed, but I tried this SICK rose under move. Mackenzie made a lot of fun of me for that beta; she's a H8R.
I don't remember which problem this was. I bet it was probably unreal.
Crushed it in my street shoes. Perfect boulder, 3 feet tall, dirty holds, awkward moves, the complete package.
Climbs like a gym problem, which I'm apparently bad at now? Had a lot of trouble remembering beta while climbing this.
Continued on the Squamish nemesis takedown tour with this thing. The Quebecois dudes may not like the far right foot, but I sure did. The sit looks nutty.
In the heat. Felt pretty hard and awkward. Big shoutout to CRSP for the lifetime of preparation to climb this sick rig. Probably not in my personal top-100 though.
On the late night prowl for new boulders. Did it quick after Phil's beta. First move crux for me. The low looks really thrutchy and dabby :/
Super difficult for me. Rocking onto heels outside of my shoulder box comes so unnaturally. Glad I no longer have to do the first move anymore.
Good problem, but difficult to find. Only takeaways are the first move being kind of strange and the fall at the finish possibly being scary.
Racing Ra really let me down. I hyped it so hard to Mackenzie and it just wasn't as fun as I remembered, not to mention to scorching heat.
First of the trip. Not quite as good as Japanese Cowboy but still a fun one.
Had to rush this one in before the boulder got bombarded by 10 Washington-ites. Climbs like a gym problem (minus the semi-tricky topout move).
In the heat! Harder than the direct. Maybe I'll super direct one day
Not 3 stars Charlie Barrett, this problem is pretty shit. It also gets really really hot.
Kind of crumbly at the bottom, kind of scrunchy in the middle, and kind of hot at the top. Maybe this is better when it's not a billion degrees.
Hooray! I've established myself as the #1 Punter on tour. Mackenzie cried when I fell off the top; she's so sympathetic and sweet!
Fun little problem. Jumping can be fun, even off small, sharp, painful crimps.

Not quite as cool as it looks, but still very good. Took a long time to figure out the top; thanks unchalked mystery crimp, you da real MVP. Thanks to Mackenzie for leading the way to the boulders, no way I would have made it by myself. P.S. - the downclimb is scarier than the actual problem, still haven't figured out a very good way off this boulder.

Don't think this move adds 2 grades (Conor said it used to add 3? Blasphemous!) unless it really makes you tired enough where the top becomes harder. I do think it adds a bit of quality, even if it's probably not the obvious start that the stand is.

Finally. Told myself in 2012 that I wasn't going to walk back up that hill until I was sure I could do it and it went 2nd go today. Forgot all the beta at the top and ended up doing it probably in as ugly a fashion as possible. Mackenzie dubbed it "ATD Round 2" which seems appropriate.
Fun climb, but there's only one move that's semi-hard (the first one). Ender's Game was weird/hard and I couldn't finish, and then I went and got a flapped on Space Race. GREAT DAY

Fun problem with a strange off-the-ground crux. Was called a "heelhook motherfucker" on this, so thanks for the compliment? I think? Thanks for the wack beta/overenthusiastic cheering meth dudes, you'll make for a great story down the road.
Pretty fun, but the weird topout limits it from getting the Recommended flag.

Nearly pseudo-flashed (I had done the first move a bunch when doing midnight train). Really fun athletic moves on good holds. More my style than Midnight Train so it felt slightly easier. Probably not V9 in my book; I don't know why it got the upgrade in the book, both problems should be V8.

Glad I got to watch Mark "Mittens" Seelos top this out before me or else I would have made a fool of myself. Fun big move to the gaston over the lip. Did it with a toe-in instead of the more common heel method.
Fun problem with kind of a strange topout. The Chiller Face and Ice House look horrifyingly scary.

Awkward, and not the fun type. Probably not V6 after the shift, and probably not as fun? It was 4 stars in the book, but climbs like a pile of crap. I'll give the benefit of the doubt and say it used to be really cool before the shift.
Slightly less awkward than Don't Worry, Be Slappy. Felt like I was actually climbing on this one. This one is def not V5 anymore. Maybe more like V4? V3?
Psuedo flash. Tried this back in 2008 on my first outdoor climbing experience. Shockingly, it felt easier now. Nice to see some measurable improvement after 8 years of falling off rocks.

Castle Peak Adventure: 2016 Edition. Tried to go to the Fun House, but it took >1 hr to get to Treasure Cove since the snow made us get lost off the trail. This problem was actually kinda cool, and it gets the Bounty Extra Soft rating! I'll take the softness for the terrible hike/wet shoes and socks/having everything else be wet/snow-covered.
This problem sucks. I mostly kept trying because Marshall kept talking about geckos. So...thanks Randy?
A+ warmup. The last move made me feel really strong. The firestones have really good rock, I just wish I was strong enough for Monster, maybe one day.
Only the awkward start (especially for those without big wingspans) prevents this from getting the Recommended flag. Was kinda scary until I re-arranged the pads, then it was pretty mild.
Probably not the "Perfect boulder problem!!" as Dave Hatchett claims, but really good nonetheless. If only the hike/bushwack/stream walk/snowshoe approach wasn't such an epic.
Pretty funky, and you can't really see most of the holds when the sun hits (which seems to be most of the day). Felt hard to me, but I also suck at this kind of climbing.

One of the first "hard" problems I ever saw (Nick Martino tried it in 2008 during my first foray in outdoor climbing in the Donner Summit climbing camp). Pretty cool setting sitting on top of snowshed. Hard first move and sharp holds after that.
Took a 30 minute nap. Then did some stupid lock-off beta to a weird bump to the lip that I almost messed up. Mackenzie made this look 10x better than me.
Had to stare at my right hand to make sure it didn't pop. The combination of the unpleasant pinch and getting swarmed by mosquitoes made this not my favorite thing.
Too scared to lunge, used a weird intermediate and went static. Stoked to run into Keenan!
Took forever to find. The directions in the guidebook are kinda whack. Missed the jug and grabbed a crimp.
First time doing it from the double undercling start. Fun day romping around with Mackenzie and Ryan. Getting better at repeating the Castle Classics.

This one looks like crap but is actually super fun. One of my new favorites at Castle. New book = softer grades? Gave both this and planet caravan V8. Both are probably more like V6. I could see the low start be in that V8/9 range but didn't do it today.
I'm sorry for disobeying your suggestions Ryan/Mackenzie :(
Mackenzie flashed in impressive fashion. I thought it was scary and hard. Topped out direct as per Ryan's orders.
Didn't pogo. Is that less cool points? Or more?
Damn that sit looks soOoOoO cool!
Another fun problem in Moe's, but it was so so so hot. Last problem of the trip, bailed after to get ice cream and drive home.
Fun problem, but god damn it was hot. One of two problems we tried in Moe's.

Saw a video of some dude doing this, calling it Anti-Future Plan, and giving it V8. Definitely doesn't match the description of Anti-Future Plan, and felt more like soft V6 than V8. Kinda highball, and a not great landing for 2.5 pads and only Mackenzie spotting. Glad I didn't fall from anywhere past half.
Bounty Extra Soft. Flashed climbing up, fell on the downclimb. Still counting it as a flash. Cool holds in the overhang, but sharp holds on the bottom and a funky top out.
Didn't top out cuz the jugs felt like choss. This problem sucked, but we did it for the name.
Climb a V3 overhang into a super awkward dynamic mantle. Tried to do the mantle static, backed down, and threw myself over. Not my favorite.
Really thuggy compression. The trick was to use the higher heel and then it wasn't so bad. Way harder than Chips.
Dry fired and busted open a couple knuckles and then did it pretty easily next go. Bounty Extra Soft, despite the lack of flash.
Apparently I can't crimp. First move felt really scrunchy and hard, even though Mackenzie could have done it in flip flops.
I can dyno! Only 1 move, but a pretty fun one.
Sooo cold. Don't usually do vertical V6 in 3 tries, so it might be a little soft. Really glad Mackenzie dragged me out here and told me to try. Best line at the Dairy sector for sure.

The ultimate inverse problem. I couldn't send until I was able to do it super pretty and never cut my feet, and Mackenzie thrutched up the finish with the I-just-want-to-be-done method. Power endurance on a short boulder.
Yeah, I think I'll pass on the terrible looking sit start and just take 7 points from the more natural stand. Not my favorite problem from Joe's
Definitely lives up to the hype. Mackenzie and I did it in the rain, so we lucked out and were the only people at the boulder. Did the long cross beta and Mackenzie did the undercling bump.

~10ish tries. Guide said V9, could see it as V8. Couldn't do the top out until I stuck the swing move from the bottom, then it was easy. Didn't know about the heel, so I just jumped for the ear hold; holding that swing was a riot. Did it right before it started snowing.
We thought this was The Hulk until it was super soft and I got suspicious. Started really low on some crimpy underclings and made a hard jab into a slot. Then it was about V2. Still kinda fun-ish
Good gym style climb with a thuggy bump move.
"Highball grade" - Mackenzie. Yeah fuck you, that first foot hold is buttery shit. Foot popped off it like 3 times.
First problem in Joe's! All the holds felt super sticky. Weird first move though, and the bucket at the top was full of water.
I did weird beta. An asian guy yelled at us. A couple dogs ate some old poop.
In the dark and out of the sun. Looked cooler than it climbed, but still a good line.
Cool looking boulder, with a big span move in the middle that felt pretty hard.
Super hot and an awkward topout
Good problem, but a little airy. Was pretty scared with my ankle, so ended up doing every move as statically as possible. Mackenzie took an unfortunate fall; big bummer :(

Second problem in Yosemite! KTS loaded me up with a full spray down, and then proceeded to pluck me off the downclimb as I had a mini adventure. Full team send (with Sage, Kevin, Vanessa, & Mackenzie).
First problem in Yosemite! Pretty fun boulder right by the river.
Finally conformed to Mark/Mackenzie's foot beta and the lock off came into reach. Wish I could have ticked the Octagon as well, guess that will wait for the next trip.
Really stupid. Not three stars. The Happies got some serious star inflation in the guidebook.
Fun problem on pockets. Woulda been a little more pleasant if it wasn't so hot.
Sorry for the shit dab-spot Mackenzie :(
Way better than Sucker Punch, but still probably not worthy of three stars.
Did it really thrutchily and gross. Mackenzie did it really smoothly and nice. Typical.
Not very fun. Why the hell did it get three stars?
This problem was named after me.

Wills told me to be honest. I didn't find it very hard so I guess this gets V7. Only the weird topout keeps this from getting the 'Recommended' flag. Feels cool to do a move that "even Daniel Woods can't do." Thanks for the confidence boost Ryan!

Should have waited 15 minutes for the top holds to cool down and I may have flashed. Fun problem with a semi-committing last move. Another beta spraydown from Mackenzie. Another try-hard devastation from Ryan.

8 tries. Decided to try after Mackenzie finished Get Carter. Love the tension and got to do two rose moves. Another instance of Mackenzie telling me what to do after I was ready to leave it for another time.
Scary as all hell pulling onto the angle change. Not my favorite style but I can see why this is popular.
Way preferred over Funky Tut. I like topout jugs.
Mackenzie flashed. I didn't. Ryan Bauer was proud of us both.
Maybe not the smoothest ascent, but a nice nighttime tick to add to the list.
One of the harder V2's out there.
Two full sessions. Would be nice to forget the first session (RIP ankle) but revenge came a couple weeks later. Fun toe-hook cross move to a nice swing.
The scary death pit is intimidating, but the problem is safer than it looks. Final day send train with Ryan and Mackenzie.
"It's like V7; it's kinda hard". Weird mini first move crux, with sharp crimps all the way through. Shoutout to REB for the parallel send on some V2, so sick.
Kinda scary dyno-ing on my bum ankle. Thanks to Mackenzie for keeping me safe when I fell, A+ spotting right there.
Whoever tossed the slash grade on this is a looney. This is hard V6. Another night send. Another Mackenzie beta influenced send. Another "oh shit everybody else is bored, I better do this now" send.
Good, not great, problem that's probably a little overrated. Topout was trickier than expected.

Was worried I wouldn't be able to climb very much because of my ankle, so I did this because it was low to the ground. Probably not worth it. Really hard first move. Really stupid second move. REB was parallel sending some highball on the other side of the boulder. We met on top. It was cute.
Channeled my inner Justin Tucker and drilled a field goal. Used the jump beta. Got nervy on the topout; are those holds going to break?
First problem in Red Rocks! Fun highball, but the downclimb is harder than the problem.
Couldn't pull off in the Lakais. I'm not as cool as Ryan Emil Bauer.
Tons of fun. Couldn't do the Mackenzie drop knee or high step steeze though, so I just pulled through and lurched, classic.
Pumpy! Had fun moving through the huge jug shelves, really nice holds.
Night send. Took 7 or 8 tries. Maybe a little soft given it went quicker than the 6s and 7s I did this weekend. Nearly punted the top. The first three moves are really cool and powerful.
Horrifying. Never again. Slab is the absolute worst. Ugh.
In the dark with a couple headlamps. Huge shoutout to Mr. Heater Portable Buddy.
If only I was as cool as Ryan Bauer and insisted on doing the Iron Method.
Beta inspired by Mackenzie. Cool invisi-hold. Send train after Mackenzie and Ryan.
Took me wayy too long. 2nd go of the 3rd session. That little slot is just too precise for me. Too bad I can't do it the Zach-The-Bod super direct method.

12 tries. Felt real soft, and I'm not a tall person, nor do I have long arms. Only took 1 session (not including the other time I was at the boulder and did the stand) and I don't climb V10 in a session. Epically punted the final V2 jump move to the victory jug, but thankfully sent next go. Really nice conditions today.

3rd try on the 3rd session. Pumped to put this one in the bag. Should have done it last time with Teddy, but it went on the quick yesterday. The top holds were in the sun, which served as nice motivation because I was freezing standing at the bottom. Did it with no drop knees and going left off the double gastons (not up to the sloper). Mackenzie's got it next time; she fell going to the jug today.
Oh man, not nearly as unpleasant as I expected. Still pretty unpleasant. Just another one to the I-only-want-to-do-this-so-I-never-have-to-again list.
5 tries after doing the direct. This one is the more fun line. Moving in, along, and out of the rail is sweet.

3 tries. Not the softest problem I've seen, but near the top of the list. Shoulda-coulda-woulda flashed if I listened to Teddy's beta instead of trying to toe. Almost blew the topout in classic fashion.
I cheated to the far right. I didn't stay direct. I climbed a more fun problem though, so screw you guidebook.
Had to seek out a V2 with a name at the Knobs, this is what delivered. V2 of 9.
Dunno if I tried this last time with Mark or not. Regardless, flashed it today and taking it as a new problem. V3 of 9.
Mackenzie's first V6 flash! Managed two thrutchy deadpoints...on a vertical face climb on knobs. Sometimes you just hold on, regardless of beta. V6 of 9.

Boulder Name: The Hardest Problem at the Knobs
Comment: More like the Softest Problem at the Knobs. It actually climbs sorta well though. V7 of 9.
Bounty Extra Soft. Did it both ways (lock off cross, and right hand dyno) and neither felt V8. Pretty fun problem though, despite the softness. V8 of 9.
First logged VB!!! This is actually a really nice looking line and a cool introduction into what knobs feel like. VB of 9.
Kinda fun. Hard to see what white spots are the holds and which are just white granite. V4 of 9.
Did it cuz it had a name and got 3 stars. V1 of 9.
Took me a few tries to stick the really huge move. Kinda feels out of control until it sticks. V5 of 9.

1 relatively quick session. Didn't use the weasel tooth; chose to use a nothing-sidepull instead. First V9 in a day, so it's probably soft, but not quite as soft as Lost. The hardest problem on the VB-V9 (Mackenzie did VB-V8) day.
V0 of 9. A quality warmup.
Pretty tough for the grade, but fun overall and the boulder is in a great setting. Really powerful, and a trickier-than-appears mantel. Deemsters looks really sweet.
Mackenzie did the stand so quickly I figured I might as well try the low. Not a whole lot harder than the stand, although I did manage to blow the topout once.
Good not great. Skipped the mono and jumped for the gaston. Bitched out and went for the less proud left exit. Mackenzie with another key beta assist.
3 tries. Fun low section with a pump crux (for me). Stoked to kick off the send train, with Caitlin and Mackenzie following up!
Tons of fun. A little awkward topping out, but a great problem, even in the sun. Was way easier than trying in the dark with Luci and 1 headlamp.
"Oh my God that's totally not the way" *proceeds to use the same beta from the sit*
Easier roof climbing into a tricky topout.
I was hoping it wasn't going to be too hard, because I was kind of sore from earlier in the day. It turned out to be pretty soft and I never ended up on top.
ON THE LITERAL LAST GO OF THE ENTIRE TRIP. One of the few things that was dry on the last day. Sent first go after Sage sprayed me down with beta. Climbs better than it looks.
If this was more than a two mover it'd be top hundy for sure. What a fun 1-2 dyno to the lip! Got all the beta from watching Mackenzie.

2 sessions. In the dark! Thanks to Mackenzie for running back to the car for the lights (even though it was for naught). Heel popped and had to hold a helicoptering foot swing. Teddy made it look so easy but it was super hard for me.
HARD HARD HARD. Three sessions and it still didn't feel easy when I finished. I suck at mantles :'(
Great problem for the Lakai tour! Good team send; really glad Kevin got to crawl between Sage and my legs. Super sexxxy.
Should have flashed this too. Really fun problem, can't believe I never tried it before.
Felt really hard 2 years ago, went 3rd go this year. Had a mini-epic topping this thing out. Big ups to Kevin on this one.
I should have flashed. Decent problem, but the dabbiness of the rocks and the deceptively tricky top out definitely take away from it's overall good-ness.
Powerful low start.
Not as good as Little Dragon, but still worth doing if you're at the boulder.

Tried it a little bit a couple years ago, and then took a couple hours this session. Finally sent after the key Mackenzie beta: "just overshoot the hold". Maybe my favorite climb from this trip? Really fun even though it's just a two mover.
4 sessions. You just gotta get lucky and stick the first move. Shitty problem, but I guess it's better than the Fuzz variations? I refuse to call this V10.
Should be in the top hundy; very fun problem.
First go from the low, which isn't surprising since it adds a V2 move into a V5...which makes it V6?
Kinda a shit problem. Did it with a dyno method. The only redeeming part is that you climb into a great V1.
Jesus this is hard in flip flops. Not a great addition to the top hundy list.
The other boulder is on! Hilarious.
I like the original better.
Didn't feel much different than the main line.
Not my favorite climb, but first Squamish boulder of 2015!

Jesus Christ this took forever. I've been trying this ~once a season since summer 2010. Feels good to finally tick it off 6 years and probably ~7 sessions later. That blind bump move has been my nemesis for so long, I'm glad we can finally be friends.
Jesus Christ I suck at slab.
I suck at lip traverses. Good thing I'm going to Squamish in a couple weeks, there are none of those there.

Oh my god so sick. Start climbing Fresh Tips Right, and then once you've done all those moves, traverse into Fresh Tips for the final couple of moves. Such a sick FA. Dave Hatchett says it's well worth doing.

Same start and finish holds as Fresh Tips; so is this problem just alternate beta on Fresh Tips? Or is Fresh Tips contrived? It's an okay problem either way. Probably harder for really small people who like crimps, much easier for everybody else (maybe V6? Felt like solid V7 to me).

Boulder Name: Tears of Tammy Fay Baker Stand
Comment: The sit kinda looks like shit to be honest. The stand was the more appealing line. Fuck the right hand bump beta, just grab the gaston and go up left hand.
Kinda fun, but this whole area is pretty bad altogether with an underratedly difficult driving approach.
If only a pad stack wasn't necessary to pull off the ground. Cool upper moves and a nice height.
Really cool Gibbs-Cave-esque first move with a squeezy foot out left. The rest of the problem is just okay though.
Kinda fun, but the top of this rock was ridiculously hot.
Funky lowball problem, but climbed better than I had expected. An added plus is that it stays in the shade.
In one very long session in the heat, thankfully it stays pretty well shaded. Took a long time to find the beta, ended up settling on some scrunchy heels.
Pretty fun, mildly sharp holds.
Good line; very sharp.
Another nice line at Boreal. Super fun hopping around on the upper jugs. Too bad the downclimb was sorta sketch.
Whoooaaaa, so much fun. I wanna come back for Maximum Overdrive.
Very nice! A little heady on the top, but a super duper line.
5 tries. Changed the right hand to the wide thumb catch and it went next go. Cool jumpy problem.
Climbs way better than it looks.
This problem, and this whole boulder, kinda suck.
Of course this one sucked. Nobody likes going to the dentist.
Both with the jump beta and Mackenzie's intermediate crimp beta.
So much power endurance! Kevin+Teddy+Me send train. Vanessa and Caitlin will do this too! Maybe my favorite 7A in Rocklands.

2 sessions. Maybe Outkast was right?Hardest I've tried on a problem. 2 full sessions, and a lot of beta from Keenan and Conor. Keenan's sneaky toe hook helped solve the redpoint crux, major assist there. Still nearly punted on the top and threw in a sketch double gaston/hand jam when I felt like giving up.
Yeeee gettin on that gaston beta steeze.
Not sure why this is such a favorite by everybody. The double toe hooks are cool, and the setting is interesting, but the rest of the climb is kind of a pile.
